He may have been there, but I do remember that we had 
great support as far as getting people set up to

03:24.459 --> 03:36.634
help us implement the system and everything. I 
don't know who to give the credit to. Bob Lacey, you

03:39.838 --> 03:41.360
probably know more than I. Bob was in charge of the 
getting the whole thing, coordinating the whole

03:44.097 --> 03:52.649
thing, and he did an excellent job from his 
standpoint on the thing. We had good cooperation

03:52.669 --> 04:02.342
from, again, other people, as I say, getting staff 
set up in the SEM's office and so forth, and it

03:52.669 --> 04:02.342
worked well. We would have never made it without 
it. Who else are scattered around the campus were

04:04.330 --> 04:10.439
good supporters of the work that you and your 
associates? Well, I always felt like the best

04:11.320 --> 04:16.267
support we had came from the associate dean within 
the college. I forgot the term. It wasn't academic

04:21.074 --> 04:22.396
council. It was the academic operations 
committee, I believe was the term. But that was a

04:28.004 --> 04:31.148
group I always enjoyed working with. They gave us 
great support, and we try to give them great

04:31.465 --> 04:36.713
support in working with their students on the 
back. Who were your favorites in that group? Oh,

04:39.156 --> 04:41.259
goodness. You have favorites, and you have some 
that are not favorites. No, but you can mention the

04:43.823 --> 04:45.285
favorites. I

04:45.365 --> 04:51.635
really enjoyed working with all the associate 
deans. I don't know that I would want to select one

04:51.835 --> 04:54.759
over the other. They were all great. great people 
to work with and, you know, additional staff in

04:55.850 --> 04:58.633
there. We mentioned Dale Noble a while ago. Dale 
was on there and people from the academic testing

05:00.574 --> 05:06.460
office were on there. It's just a great group to 
work with. Alright, in your own personal

05:10.023 --> 05:17.730
recollection, what are some of your proudest 
moments of the years you worked at A&M?

05:24.176 --> 05:25.097
I think that the The nicest thing that I had is I had a 
great staff to work with the whole time I was there.

05:31.259 --> 05:39.850
You mentioned Ms. Mitchell, Mr. Gilwood, Mr. 
Harvey Strigler, Ms. Luna Dean, they were the four

05:31.259 --> 05:39.850
heads of my department. And Ms. Jean Ringer, we 
added the international on later on. And they were

05:44.537 --> 05:45.899
the heads of the departments. They were just 
exceptional to work with.

05:51.065 --> 05:57.291
I think the greatest accomplishment that we had 
that really helped us more was getting CEMS in

05:51.065 --> 05:57.291
operation. Because, I mean, we were floundering 
as far as paperwork was concerned. It used to be

06:02.756 --> 06:10.403
when early days, if you wanted to look for a file, if 
you called for it and got it within 30 minutes or an

06:02.756 --> 06:10.403
hour, you were lucky. After we got CEMS in, if we 
called it up and it wasn't on the screen in five or

06:11.544 --> 06:20.312
ten seconds, we thought, my goodness, it's 
terrible because it's so slow.

06:22.722 --> 06:34.661
We had,

06:22.722 --> 06:34.661
again, most of the time the office was, the work 
which we did was just great. I had often mentioned

06:34.861 --> 06:48.983
to people, you know, I really never looked for a, in 
moving to another director's admission job,

06:34.861 --> 06:48.983
because I didn't think it was any better than what I 
had here. We were very fortunate in that as we grew,

06:49.469 --> 06:55.217
we had facilities to take care of the students. We 
had a good building program there, but we didn't

06:55.237 --> 07:00.685
have to cut back on the enrollment too early on. 
Eventually, we got to the point where we did. And

07:02.488 --> 07:04.771
once you get to that point, it gets a whole lot 
tougher. I enjoyed the freedom, which I always

07:04.791 --> 07:11.361
felt I had, to make the decisions, to run the office 
and everything. I appreciate Ed's guidance there

07:11.381 --> 07:19.172
and Gary's whenever he came and took over. a very 
enjoyable experience. Again, it would be hard to

07:21.516 --> 07:28.542
name the people that you enjoy working with 
because there were so many. Do you remember any

07:28.562 --> 07:33.567
particular events that you're delighted that you 
were there to witness? Any kind of event? Were

07:37.870 --> 07:45.097
involved in missions or not?

07:45.117 --> 07:48.940
Gosh, I don't know what that would have been. As we 
mentioned a while ago, I always went to

07:49.460 --> 07:51.522
graduation. I missed one graduation, I think, in 
22 years. That was because I was sick. But I always

07:59.131 --> 08:08.562
had a part in the graduation ceremony, and 
therefore I went to, whether we had three a year or

07:59.131 --> 08:08.562
whether we had seven a year, I went to every one of 
them. And that's one thing I always enjoyed going

08:08.582 --> 08:11.085
to. I don't think I... They never feel any 
resentment as part of the job, but I really, I

08:13.270 --> 08:19.236
probably would have gone otherwise, I think. But I 
really enjoyed that, just to see the students, the

08:19.296 --> 08:30.987
parents, and the faculty members that did too, and 
the joy of seeing them reach their goal and getting

08:19.296 --> 08:30.987
there as one with me and them. Okay. What advice 
would you give to current and future AM

08:32.849 --> 08:39.615
administrators about commencements? I think the 
greatest thing we do is having it like we do, where

08:41.080 --> 08:54.054
the student gets their diploma, walks across the 
stage, gets recognition from parents, fellow

08:41.080 --> 08:54.054
classmates, and faculty. I think this is the best 
thing we do. I got my master's and doctorate from

08:57.517 --> 09:07.628
another institution, and it was a stand up and sit 
down affair. I think it's just one of the nicest

09:08.502 --> 09:23.256
things we do to let the parents have the experience 
of seeing their son or daughter receive their

09:08.502 --> 09:23.256
diploma from an individual president of the 
university in this case. And I think they leave

09:23.276 --> 09:33.745
that last official act in their relation with A&M, 
I think the whole family leaves there feeling

09:23.276 --> 09:33.745
good. They've got the diploma, they don't have a 
facsimile, they've got the real diploma. One of

09:38.624 --> 09:51.116
the little touches that Dr. Williams used to do 
that I copied wherever I went was near the end when

09:38.624 --> 09:51.116
he would ask the parents of the first generation 
graduates to stand. And that was always touching

09:52.157 --> 10:06.150
because you'd see some women reaching for their 
handkerchief to dry a tear because I am one of those

09:52.157 --> 10:06.150
and I know how special it was to my parents that I got 
to go to college. Let's see, anything that you can

10:07.008 --> 10:12.474
think of that you would change, you would have 
changed? Oh, there's probably a lot of things I

10:14.176 --> 10:17.861
would have changed and done differently. But I've 
always, I view it just like I did with a lot of

10:18.522 --> 10:23.207
things, kind of raising new kids. I think I did the 
best I could under the circumstances with the

10:23.928 --> 10:29.234
knowledge I had at that time. Are there any 
organizational changes or...

10:36.269 --> 10:47.499
decision path changes, you'd...

10:47.519 --> 10:55.906
There are, again, a lot of different ways you can 
decide on, if you're talking about the admissions

10:47.519 --> 10:55.906
process, how you can do it.

10:59.609 --> 11:01.731
Like, where does that report now? It reports... Is 
it still academic? Still reporting to the It's

11:05.530 --> 11:06.431
still academic. It's still courts of the provost, 
and I think that's where it should be. I think it's

11:09.195 --> 11:13.840
an academic function, and I think it should be 
following that. I think it's at the provost level

11:14.541 --> 11:18.747
is probably appropriate. I don't think it should 
be at the president's level. I think he's got other

11:20.389 --> 11:22.151
things to deal with.

11:25.095 --> 11:32.584
I think that the organization which we had with the 
dean and the admissions and the registrar work

11:32.851 --> 11:33.792
fine. There may be times when it would be better, 
and it depended on what the dean's function is,

11:33.892 --> 11:46.048
whether it would be better or whether to have an 
admissions and reporting directly to the provost

11:33.892 --> 11:46.048
and a registrar. I didn't have any strong feelings 
on that.

11:51.935 --> 11:54.358
Let's see, we're getting near the end. Let's make 
believe that somebody gave you a lot of money that

12:02.281 --> 12:17.575
you are to give to A&M

12:02.281 --> 12:17.575
a lot of money, hundreds of thousands of dollars, 
but you decide what it's going to be used for, what

12:02.281 --> 12:17.575
would you direct it to? Where would you put it and 
for what purpose?

12:24.962 --> 12:29.486
My personal feeling is it should probably go to 
scholarships. Based on? not necessarily

12:31.019 --> 12:32.581
academics. I mean, academic is a priority on the 
thing. But there are many students, I think, here

12:37.669 --> 12:43.257
who could do a whole lot better if they had a little 
financial aid. And I would be looking to try to help

12:44.299 --> 12:48.225
those. I think that Are you saying more 
opportunity awards? The opportunity award type

12:52.753 --> 12:55.015
scholarship, yeah. Those students who have 
proven ability, lack of cash, and other support

12:55.135 --> 13:05.247
possibly on the thing, which would help those out. 
