Alright. My problem is I don't remember a lot of 
stories on the things. Alright, let's conclude

17:42.414 --> 17:43.935
with this. As you look back now, those 22 years, 
what do you think was your responsibility?

17:53.505 --> 17:56.929
What role do you think you and your staff played for 
Texas A&M?

18:00.993 --> 18:14.410
I think that our role was to try to select a group of 
students who could come in to Texas A&M and be

18:00.993 --> 18:14.410
successful. Successful in this sense was that 
they could receive their bachelor's degree from

18:14.431 --> 18:21.980
Texas A&M. Any other success they have might be, 
that's up to them. But what we wanted to do and what

18:25.885 --> 18:30.932
we would like to do is to select X number of students 
and four years later have them receive their

18:31.756 --> 18:35.801
bachelor's degree. That's not realistic for a lot 
of reasons, I think. But we felt like our job was to

18:39.224 --> 18:50.877
try to select students who could

18:39.224 --> 18:50.877
best use the facilities which we had here. That is, 
they could profit by the faculty, they could

18:51.458 --> 19:00.328
profit by living here, all the other things which 
go to make up the education process. Did anybody at

19:00.494 --> 19:08.688
any other group at A&M have any responsibility 
more important than the one y'all had? Well, I

19:10.993 --> 19:14.399
think that the faculty had a tremendous 
responsibility once we got them here. But was it

19:14.899 --> 19:17.063
more important than y'all's? See, I think y'all 
were the quality controllers. Well, I think that

19:20.149 --> 19:22.713
we were. I think it was our job to make a select the 
group, and then somebody else takes and nurtures

19:25.823 --> 19:30.665
them and can go on from there. How are you? Good. 
Let's quit with that.

